MICRODOSING 🍄. Soooo many of you were curious and interested
in my recent protocol micro dosing psilocybin (a.k.a. magic mushrooms). There were lots of good questions so I thought I would share a little of my experience.
A few asked “Did the mushrooms make me ‘feel funny’ or ‘trip-out’?” Simply put, no. What I personally experienced, especially for the first few days, was what I would describe as a warm, happy feeling with a boost of energy. Just a really good mood. I was amazed with my increased focus, concentration, mental clarity, and creativity. I also noticed my digestion improved during the protocol. The brand I used has the ingredient Niacin, which promotes metabolism (And who doesn’t need a boost there?! 🤪)

Another question was my protocol (micro-dosing schedule) & dosage. I chose the Stamets schedule which is 4 days of micro-dosing (I chose Mon-Thurs) and 3 days off (Fri-Sun). I continued this for a month and then took a complete break (Which I am still on – not for long, though.) The Brainstack blend from @my.supply.co recommends 1-4 capsules per day. I did 2 capsules for most of my protocol.

I chose Brainstack’s blend specifically because of its added adaptogens, superfoods and vitamins. If you are going to micro-dose you might as well get the best quality and one that has added ingredients. Brainstacks blend includes all Organic Psilocybe Cubensis, Lion’s Mane, Sage, Cinnamon, and Naturally-derived Niacin. There is more information on @my.supply.co website that explains what the benefits are of each of those ingredients. They also have an entire blog section called “Learn”that has LOTS of information on all things plant medicine. I’ll link their website in my bio for you if you wanted to read up or search something specific.

Hope this helps anyone who is curious about micro-dosing. 
If you are interested in ordering from @my.supply.co “Krystalsyoga” will save you 15% off anything on their site.

INTERMITTENT FASTING. While I’m no expert or dietician I do get a lot of questions around my diet so I thought I’d share what I do, and what I know. 
I’ve been intermittent fasting for a couple years now and it has evolved over time. I’m learning a lot as go. I typically try to fast 15-17 hours a day. Basically just think an extended rest and digest. 😌 It’s a simple way to allow your body time to fully digest and use its own energy source before adding more to the metaphorical “tank”. ⛽️
If you are NEW to fasting my recommendation is to start by pushing your breakfast one hour. ⏰ So if you typically eat at 8am, try pushing it to 9am for a couple weeks until that feels easy and then go ahead and push it again until you’ve reached your desired fast length (14-18 hours is plenty) START SLOW. 🚦
Now all that being said, men have a 24 HOUR 🌞sex hormone cycle and women a 28 DAY 🌓sex hormone cycle. TESTOSTERONE LOVES fasting. PROGESTERONE does NOT 👎🏻. It actually requires carbs, hence why we women crave certain foods before our cycle. Progesterone is asking for it🍏. So here’s where it gets a little complicated. MEN, you can go ahead and fast daily, your body will love this. WOMEN, need to fast along with their cycle. What do I do?
15-17 hours a day. Let’s be clear, if I wake up and I’m really hungry well before my fasting period is over - I will eat, but most days I fast until noon or more drinking lots of healthy fluids 💦(water, tea, AG1, bubly, coffee)
The week before my cycle I drop that fasting window to help raise hormone levels. I will typically be hungry all day everyday. 
Once my cycle begins or as it’s ending I begin fasting again and then I’ll add in a 36 HOUR fast because that feels good in my body and is a good reset and hunger has dissipated with hormones. 
I know you are intelligent 👏🏻 and know not to break your fast with shitty junk food or binging. The best way to break your fast with light/small portions of protein and easy to digest foods 🥗🍗 Happy fasting and I hope this helps someone interested in intermittent fasting! 
Krys 🤍

3 TIPS that helped me catch some extra air time in my handstand! 🤸🏻‍♀️🙌🏻

1. Spider the fingers.🕷️Press palms and finger tips down while allowing the middle knuckle in each finger lift. Your fingers will look like spider legs. This creates a “breaking” action helping you from falling forward. 
2. Elbows back, biceps forward. Do your best to rotate your arms externally. This helps lock 🔒 your arms straight. The straighter the arms the more bone strength (stacking) you’ll use. (I’m still working hard on this one myself 🥵)
3. Shift your shoulders PAST your wrists when you hop up. This is all about alignment. If your shoulders are too far back when you kick up you might not get enough momentum to get those feet straight up 🙃⬆️

I hope this helps ☺️🤸🏻‍♀️
Happy handstanding! 🫶🏻

A year from now you are going to wish you started today.
I know it’s hard to start. I know it’s scary to do the thing. To say what’s uncomfortable.  To put yourself out there to fail or be criticized. To leave. To let go. To give up the story that once was and have the courage to rewrite one new. 

But you know what else I know? That the scary thing isn’t really that scary. Being uncomfortable makes us grow. It teaches us how to expand, become wiser, more comfortable in discomfort, how powerful and capable we actually are. That those you thought would criticize might actually cheer you on, or you’ll discover those who will cheer for you. That you might actually create something really freakin awesome, something that you are so dang proud of. That leaving was best decision you might ever make. That letting go allowed room for more, for better to flow in. 
That stories are just that. Stories. And that we have the power to write a sad shitty story for our lives OR that we can be the hero of our own by taking chances and having courage and faith in own inner authors. 
That is powerful stuff my friends. 
I’m gonna ask you to be vulnerable and share your dream. Where do you wanna be, who do you wanna be, what do you want, a year from now?

Story time. What a night. Your girl over here has barely slept 🥱. It was a gorgeous spring day yesterday, so I left the back door open a little to get some fresh air in. At some point my curious kitten 🐈‍⬛ wandered out and by the time I realized, she was sadly, missing 🥺. I search the neighborhood but couldn’t find her. I hoped she would come home before dinner, but she didn’t. My son, Jacob, and I trolled and polled the neighborhood again and met some really sweet neighbors, none of which had seen our kitty. We searched until dark 🌑. Heartbreakingly 💔, we went to bed knowing that she was out there, and that temperatures were going below zero for the night. If you have ever had a pet not come home at night, you’ll know how upsetting this can be 😭. I felt awful, thinking she was cold and lost. I live near the river valley and it’s home to predators and there is lots of room get directionless. I slept with the window open, one ear listening all night for a tiny meow or a little jingle of a bell from her collar. My other kitty 😿, noticibly disturbed, was softly meowing for his sister and searching the house and back door. Around 3:45 am I thought I heard something 😯. I jumped out of bed and looked out the window. Nothing 🫤. I decided to go outside with a mason jar of cat food. I shook it and listened. Let me tell you, the world is an eerie place and mezmorizingly quiet at 4:00am. I shook it again, called her name (which she doesn’t answer to anyway 🙄) and again, listened. Nothing. Deep. Dark. Nothingness. Again, a shake, a call, and listen. I heard something. A tiny meow? 🧐 Shake. Listen. Yes! it was indeed a tiny meow! 🙌🏻 hallelujah, there she was! 😍She found her way home! 🙏🏻 Safe and sound. I crawled into bed and once my happy heart ❤️ stopped beating hard I fell into a short but peaceful slumber 😴. 
Long story short; The cat came back the very next day. 😅

How Yoga changed me…

Far from an athlete. The first time I stepped on my mat I couldn’t touch my toes. I was depressed, sad, overwhelmed, confused, angry, and really just there to try and escape my life - mentally and physically. 💔

That first class was rough. My teacher always says that the practice is simple, but it is not easy and the truth in that was there on the very first day. And many days after. 

My first year of practicing was a bit of a dance. Coming to practice as often as I could for a while, and then falling back into not practicing at all. I suppose all transformation starts with that sort of vacillating back-and-forth. Between the old and the new. 

Once I finally took my practice seriously, and committed myself to it, I begin to change. 🦋 What Yoga taught me..

•Yoga taught me release, letting go, and non-attachment. That it was not only OK to move on and change, but NECESSARY. 🙏🏻
• Yoga taught me strength. As I began to get stronger on my mat, I started to feel a power inside me rumbling. Giving me courage in so many ways. ✨
• Yoga, taught me grace, humility, and a humbleness. The physical practice of yoga humbles me every time I step on my mat. It teaches me that stumbling and falling are part of the process. There is grace and beauty and the transitions. It’s not about the poses. It’s how you move from one to the next. On your mat and off. And as I have those breakthroughs, I’m also reminded of my limitations. And that is the work. ❤️‍🩹
• Yoga taught me how to find my voice. Sharing on this platform, becoming a teacher, speaking in front of a room full of people, and letting go of toxic relationships by using my voice has been one of my biggest challenges and greatest gifts. 💝
• Yoga taught me to like myself. Being my own friend, finding my independence and autonomy. I am learning to like what I see in the mirror in the words that come out of my mouth - for me that never came easy. 🫶🏻

 2. Land with right foot into in a sorta twisted pistol squat
3. Move right into joy pose balancing on right knee
4. Back to cobra as you bend left knee
5. Flip over into wild thing (right leg straight)
6. Back through cobra to crouching down dog
7. Repeat other side
8. Continue forever 😁

Healing is messy. It’s not pretty pictures on Instagram and Pinterest. Sometimes, it’s mascara tears running down your face, days of laying in bed with the covers over your head because it feels like “I can’t do this, it’s too hard”.
Whether you are just starting to heal or you’ve been working on it for sometime, just know that it is not an easy journey, it’s going to get messy, you’re going to have days where you want to just give up and quit but in the end, the woman you become because of it - is all worth it. 
If you take the time to work on yourself, and you go deep, and you heal the traumas, and the hurts, and the wounds that you didn’t even know are still in there, you’ll be amazed at what you start to attract after you start believing in what you deserve and what you are capable of. 
Hunny, know that you are NOT alone. You are not the only one out there that is feeling like this. There are so many women that are in the same exact position but don’t know where to turn or what to do. As you begin to do the work and you begin to heal, you can be that for others. You can be that guiding light. Be that queen energy and shine your light on the world. It’s a ripple effect. As you heal and share that healing that’s going to allow someone else to begin to heal, and share their light.
Sometimes you have to give yourself that permission to say “Damn. I’m stuck and I don’t know what the hell to do. I need help”. It doesn’t make you weak, it doesn’t make you any less of a woman, it doesn’t make you any less of a mother. That is some c.o.u.r.a.g.e.o.u.s shit, whenever you can say ‘I need help’.”
Start where you are. Start with hands shaking, start with voice trembling. Just start. Let this be the year you take those deeper breaths, with open eyes, say yes, running with total abandon in the direction of the courage you have longed to find for years.

8 awesome reasons to go on a Yoga Retreat 
1. If you’re a beginner, you’ll gain confidence and a solid foundation for your yoga practice with the close guidance of a supportive teacher. 
2. If you’re more experienced, you’ll deepen in your practice, and quickly! You’ll have your teachers full attention, and you can ask questions and learn more than you can in a usual class. 
3. You’ll make new friends. Making friends as an adult is hard, let’s be honest. On a yoga retreat you have the space and time to build close friendships with new awesome people.
4. You’ll raise your vibration. The positive energy that grows from moving, meditating, eating nourishing food, experiencing awe and connecting with like-minded people can feel like MAGIC. 
5. You can heal. People go on retreats for all kinds of reasons and a yoga Retreat is often a place where you can experience real healing. 
6. Detox and de-stress. The settings of a yoga retreat is a perfect space and place to nourish your body, relax, and experience peace and joy. 
7. Disconnect to reconnect. As you disconnect from the hustle and bustle of life and technology, yoga retreats offer the time and space to reconnect with nature and reconnect with your true self.
8. Motivation and transformation. Participating in a structured retreat with yoga at its core, encourages a routine with tangible, feel good results. Providing you with elements to add to your lifestyle when you get back home.

Instead of asking, ‘Have I worked hard enough to deserve to rest?’, I’ve started asking, ‘Have I rested enough to do my most loving, meaningful work?’
@NicolaJaneHobbs

“Resting” can look different for all of us. For me, resting, isn’t necessarily laying down, couch time, or not doing anything. Resting, for me, is balancing work-life-play. It’s practising more and teaching less. It’s stepping away from the screen more often to do things that light me up. It’s wearing flowy warm comfortable clothes. It’s intermittent fasting (giving digestion a rest). It’s sleepy time meditations. 
It took me a really long time to finally figure out and accept that what’s balance for MY life is not what’s balanced for everyone else’s life. 
I choose my balance on the daily. What deserves time and attention TODAY and I focus on that. Some weeks I realize I’ve  chose work more than play and family. Some weeks I’ve chosen family more than the others. It’s all balancing. It’s all resting.

Wanna join me? Here are the rules.
1. Stick to a healthy diet. No cheat meals. No alcohol. Do this for 75 days.
2. Drink a gallon of water every day. Do this for 75 days.
3. Do two 45 minute workouts a day. The second one MUST be outside. Do this for 75 days.
4. Take a progress picture. Do this for 75 days.
5. Read 10 pages of a self betterment book every day. Do this for 75 days.
Miss a day? You have to start over at day one again.
